        />
        <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
          Navigate through the pages to learn more about me, get a detailed overview of the topic, see how mass media covers it, and get in touch with any questions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
);

const AboutPage = () => (
    <div className="animate-fade-in p-4 md:p-8 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <SectionHeader title="About the Creator" subtitle="Background and Motivation" />
        <div className="bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-100">
            <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">Who I Am</h2>
            <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                I am a college student currently studying Mass Media and Communications. This website is a key component of a project for my Mass Media & Society class. I have always been fascinated by the power of media to shape public perception, and this project provides an opportunity to dive deep into one of the most influential forms of media in our daily lives.
            </p>

            <ImageWithCaption 
                src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519389950473-47ba0277781c?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop"
                alt="A student working on a laptop in a collaborative environment."
                caption="This project combines academic research with digital media creation. [Source: Unsplash]"
            />

            <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4 mt-8">Why This Topic?</h2>
            <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                I chose to focus on the effects of advertising on consumer culture because it's a force that impacts every single one of us, every day. From the shows we watch to the feeds we scroll, we are constantly interacting with persuasive messages. I wanted to dig deeper to understand the mechanisms behind this influence, its historical roots, and its consequences for society. This project is an opportunity to critically examine a part of our world that is often taken for granted and to understand how it constructs our reality, values, and desires.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
);

const TopicOverviewPage = () => (
    <div className="animate-fade-in p-4 md:p-8 max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <SectionHeader title="Topic Overview" subtitle="Advertising's Role in Consumer Culture" />
        <div className="bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-lg border border-gray-100 space-y-8">
            <div>
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">Background: What, Who, and When?</h2>
                <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                    Consumer culture is a social and economic order that encourages the acquisition of goods and services in ever-greater amounts. Advertising is its primary engine. <strong>(What)</strong> It is a form of communication used to persuade an audience to take some new action. <strong>(When)</strong> While rudimentary forms of advertising have existed for centuries, modern advertising began to take shape in the late 19th and early 20th centuries with the rise of mass production and mass media like newspapers and radio. <strong>(Who)</strong> Initially driven by manufacturers and retailers, the industry now involves a complex ecosystem of brands, advertising agencies, media companies, and data brokers, all working to capture consumer attention and spending.
                </p>
                <SourceCitation>Williams, R. (1980). Advertising: The Magic System. In *Problems in Materialism and Culture*.</SourceCitation>
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">The "Why" and "How": Mechanisms of Influence</h2>
                <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                   <strong>(Why)</strong> At its core, advertising works by creating associations between a product and a desirable feeling, lifestyle, or identity. It doesn't just sell a car; it sells freedom, adventure, and status. <strong>(How)</strong> This is achieved through sophisticated techniques including emotional appeals, the use of psychological triggers like scarcity ("limited time only!"), social proof (testimonials and influencer marketing), and the constant repetition of messages across multiple platforms. By identifying or creating problems and positioning products as the necessary solutions, advertising shifts consumer perception from mere 'wants' to essential 'needs,' embedding brands into the fabric of daily life.
                </p>
                <SourceCitation>Berger, J. (2016). *Contagious: Why Things Catch On*. Simon & Schuster.</SourceCitation>
            </div>

            <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 pt-4 border-t border-gray-200">Required Sources</h2>
